The design and construction of sustainable built environments that are more environmentally, socially, and economically responsible over their full life cycle from extraction of raw construction materials to end of life management is increasingly desirable worldwide. With the aim of discovering new ways to integrate industrial ecology and sustainability within the multi-scale design and construction of built environments, a 3-day workshop was organized by the Center for Innovative Materials Research (CIMR) of Lawrence Technological University and the Civil and Environmental Engineering Department at Stanford University, in conjunction with Technion, Israel Institute of Technology, Haifa, Israel.



The workshop program was broken up into six distinct sessions.  These sessions were;

(1)  Sustainable Material Systems and Ecologies

(2)  Sustainable and Resilient Structural Design

(3)  Integrated Building Systems and Urban Environment

(4)  Probabilistic Design and Risk-based Analysis of Sustainable Built Environments

(5)  Integrated Modeling and Analysis Tools for Sustainable Built Environments

(6)  Sustainability Engineering in Developed vs. Developing Countries



At the conclusion of each day of the workshop, individual breakout sessions were held on each of these 6 session topics to allow participants to reflect on the session presentations and discuss a potential future pathway for collaborative research, demonstration, and education. These common themes among the individual breakout sessions were;

(1)  The need to develop and research the value proposition of sustainable built environments;

(2)  The need for appropriate definition of metrics of sustainable built environments at multiple scales;

(3)  The need to change the focus of sustainability from top-of-the-pyramid to bottom-of-the-pyramid;

(4)  The need to change engineering education globally to respond to sustainability-focused engineering challenges.



Additionally, the workshop participants from the United States were asked to submit a brief, individual whitepaper summarizing their vision for ongoing research collaboration and research plans in the area of industrial ecology tools for multi-scale sustainable built environments.  The whitepaper comments can be summarized under three main topics;

(1)   Research on the design of sustainable built environments should have increased focus on bottom-of-the pyramid solutions, particularly for fast growing cities in developing countries.

(2)   New funding models are needed for the type of highly interdisciplinary and collaborative research required for sustainable built environments.  Specifically, joint calls for research between US and Israeli funding agencies are needed.

(3)   Increasingly, human behavior must be incorporated into research on the sustainable built environment.



A major intellectual contribution of the workshop was to increase education and awareness of sustainable built environment issues both within and outside of academia. The above research recommendations and strategies were considered to be most suitable in the context of socio-economic and environmental considerations. One important workshop product was a set of recommendations summarizing the best practices and acceptable methods for implementing innovative designs and materials in the multi-scale design, construction, and operation of sustainable built environments.  These are detailed in the full project report.  The three-day long workshop also brought together researchers and thinkers to discuss topics on industrial ecology, such as probabilistic life cycle analysis (LCA) and probabilistic sustainability design approaches, and their use when creating innovative materials in green building design and sustainable infrastructure design in environmentally sensitive and resource-limited areas.



